There is no such scene in Homer, nor, unless I mistake‚ in any other poetry before that of Christian chivalry. And it is thrown into high relies by the contrast with the savagery of Turnus‚¹ who allows no one but himself to slay the young prince Pallas and eries “Would that his father were here to see him fall.”

In the crowning scene of the Aeneid this cruelty recoils on Turnus himself. As he lies defeated and begs for mercy, AEneas stays his hand and is about to spare even Turnus. But his eye falls on the baldric of Pallas which Turnus had taken for himself, and his grief for Pallas rouses again the temper of the warrior and the judge.
